CREATING THE OBJECT MODULE FOR PDS
-------------------------------------

Concatenate the files

   create.f  define.f  depth.f   done.f    equal.f  fcn.f     getss.f 
   init.f    maxlen.f  order.f   pds.f     quick.f  reads.f   result.f 
   right.f   scaled.f  search.f  shrink.f  sort.f   writes.f
 
from the PDS distribution in a single new file named pdsd.f.  Compile
(but do not link) pdsd.f. The resulting object file pdsd.o 
should then be placed in either the user-defined directory $PDS or in 
$CUTEST/objects/(architecture)/(precision)/ for the architecture and 
precsion you intend to use.

PDS is not available in single precision.

USING THE PDS INTERFACE TOOL
-------------------------------

Suppose you wish to solve the problem written in SIF format contained
in the file probname.SIF.

The PDS interface tools require two input files:

   probname.SIF   specifies the problem in SIF format
   PDS.SPC        sets values for PDS run-time parameters

If no PDS.SPC file is present in the current directory, the default
version is copied from the $CUTEST/src/pds directory. 
This default file is as follows:

   0.00001   TOL     the stopping tolerance for the step size 
       500   MAXITR  the maximum number of iterations allowed
         2   TYPE    0 given 1 right 2 regular 3 scaled rt (1,2 & 3 constructed)
       1.0   SCALE   if type not 0 scale contains base length (and orientation)
         4   DEBUG   flag 0 (none) 1 2 3 and 4 give progressively more info.
       256   SSS     number of points used in the search strategy.

The reader is referred to the paper quoted below and the code itself if he or 
she wishes to modify these parameters.

To run with CUTEst, use the runcutest command with the -p pds option.
See the man page for runcutest for more details of other options.

